sentences: He got the nickname "Butch" after Machine Gun Butch, a character in the film The Big House (1930).
When he was 21, he married Jessie, for whom he bought a house in Philadelphia in 1950.
In 1938, Ballard began playing with Louis Armstrong's band The Dukes.
In 1941, he began playing with the Cootie Williams Orchestra, performing with Ella Fitzgerald, Sarah Vaughan, Dinah Washington and Pearl Bailey.
In 1950, Ballard received a telephone call from Duke Ellington who had heard of Ballard from his son Mercer.
Ballard continued to play with Ellington in 1952–1953 and made recordings with him, such as "Satin Doll.
"In the 1960s, Ballard began leading his own band in Philadelphia.
On December 1, 2006, Ballard received the Mellon Jazz Community Award for his musical career and his continued education of young jazz musicians.

sentences: George Edward "Butch" Ballard (December 26, 1918 – October 1, 2011) was an American jazz drummer who played with Louis Armstrong, Count Basie, and Duke Ellington.
When he was about 10 years old, Ballard's father bought him a set of drums from a pawnbroker and he began to take lessons for 75 cents each.
At around 16 years old, Ballard listened to Herb Thornton's band at the Boys Club in Philadelphia.
For the following few months, he carried his drums across Philadelphia to rehearse.
He performed with them for a few years.
Ballard became a music teacher in the mid-1980s and saw about 12 students a week.
In his later years, he also played with the Philadelphia Legends of Jazz Orchestra.
